Someone came to fix the floor in my kitchen, so I'm going to pretend I still have a job and work from home while reviewing Too Hot to Handle.
If I manage to open this damned file. (Damned OneDrive.)
The translation of "*voix de pirate* J'y suis" from French to English is:  "Pirate voice: I'm here."
And that's where it starts to drill super hard. Great!
Her passive-aggressive way of turning my air purifier all the way up makes me uncomfortable, but it smells like sawdust, so it's justified even if she's anti-mask. And besides, I really need to protect myself, don't I?
I really want to go back to bed, but I can't until he leaves.
The positive point is that I have finally finished re-reading Chapter 4!
Chapter five is long, but full of suspense. Good work.
Working on find-replace for ... ➡️ ellipse character, and there are 54 of them in this chapter 😅
But anyway, that's how it is. The most natural-sounding speeches are usually disjointed, especially when people let themselves go with their emotions.
The artisan is vacuuming, and with a bit of luck, he will have finished soon.
He went out (as I understand it) to cut something. So I took a look to see where he was at. It's far from being finished :(.
Less than 7 pages left for chapter five. It's still my favorite chapter, and it's quite well-developed. Just some adjustments for formatting, and minor changes to put it in the active voice and improve conciseness. That said, I might take a break and have a cup of tea, but the guy is still fiddling around in my kitchen.
He has just started vacuuming again. I hope that's a good sign.
The artisan is gone!
He told me he had made an estimate for the entire floor, but the owners were cheap and only paid for the small damaged corner near the door. It's definitely better.
The house is airing out, and my air purifier is running in the kitchen while I enjoy a cup of tea in the garden!
